{"key":"processedPost-13238375","value":{"id":13238375,"first":13235414,"last":13240646,"when":1285298222,"utime":"09/24/10 06:17 AM","content":"Mold spores have a very hard time germinating on coir.&nbsp; The main point in pasteurization therefore is to 'cook' the coir, thus releasing the nutrients within for the mycelium.&nbsp; This is why the boiling water in a bucket thing <i>sorta works</i>, but not as well as if you'll hydrate the coir to the correct moisture level and then pasteurize it in jars or bags at 140F to 160F for sixty to ninety minutes.&nbsp; This will help to release more of the food within to the mycelium and result in faster colonization.<br /><br />If your coir is contaminating during colonization, the most likely cause is that your grain spawn is contaminated.&nbsp; Always smell each spawn jar after breaking it up.&nbsp; It should smell like fresh mushrooms.&nbsp; If it smells like garbage, it's contaminated with bacteria and if it smells like dirt, it's contaminated with molds.<br />RR","title":"Re: spawn ratios for better success"}}